    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm studying for my structural mechanics exam. can u explain why we actually need to add steel rebar to concrete foundations? like why isnt the concrete itself enough to handle the loads? im a bit confused about the relationship between compressive and tensile strength here.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I'd be happy to help with that! Concrete is actually quite strong when it comes to compression, but it has a weak point when it comes to tension. Steel rebar is added to concrete foundations because steel has a much higher tensile strength than concrete. When concrete is subjected to forces that cause it to stretch or pull apart (tension), the steel reinforcement helps to hold it together and prevent cracking or failure. This combination of materials creates a stronger, more durable foundation that can better handle both compression and tension loads. So, the steel rebar essentially acts as a support to the concrete, making the foundation much more resilient to the forces it will encounter.",
      "source": "target",
